Our question is primarily whether CD presence affects the rest of the microbiome, so we might want to prune the Cdiff reads before doing our alpha and beta divsity analysis. This pruning will likely make very little difference to the results, because Cdiff tends to be low a very low percentage of the community:

##      Min.   1st Qu.    Median      Mean   3rd Qu.      Max. 
## 0.0002346 0.0006569 0.0061083 0.0107715 0.0123313 0.0641462

and the alpha and beta diversity measures we use are not sensitive to a low-proportion taxa. However, to confirm that our results are not substantially affected by CD abundance in the profiles, we will run our analyses both ways.

##   ASV82 ASV1962 ASV2073 
##    TRUE    TRUE    TRUE

Convert profiles to proportions, and get versions aggregated to the genus and family ranks

Alpha and beta diversity across hosts

Alpha diversity

We use the diversity() function in the vegan package to calculate the Inverse Simpson diversity index at the ASV, Genus, and Family level and add these to sample_data(ps).

The Inverse Simpson index is not sensitive to rare taxa and so should not be significantly affected by read depth in the range of read depths of our samples. We can confirm by plotting diversity against read depth and making sure there is not an increasing pattern,

We’ll order the host species from most to least diverse (based on the median over all ranks and samples);

Alpha diversity and C. difficile in canines and equines

Here we test for an association of C. difficile with alpha diversity in canines and equines, the only species with a substantial number of CD+ samples,

First, get a data frame subset to just canines and equines,

Create a 2-panel figure, showing diversity in CD- and CD+ samples, at the three taxonomic ranks, for the two hosts,

Beta diversity and C. difficile in canines and equines

Here we perform a permanova test using the adonis2 function in vegan to identify if there is a significant difference in the microbiome profiles between CD+ and CD- samples within animal groups canine and equine. As above, we use Bray-Curtis similarity, but we only examine the ASV-level profiles.
